                <h4>How does Turkey have an economy?</h4>
                <p>Turkey's most important economic resource is the tourism industry. It attracts an average of about 2 million tourists and tourists annually, which brings in a lot of profit and turnover. Turkey is a traditional-modern country and in general, its economy is based on the agricultural industry and is constantly expanding in addition to the tourism industry. So that 5% of the country's workforce is in the agricultural industry. Flax, tobacco, olives, etc. are important agricultural products of this country. Turkey's export products and services also include garment production, equipment, raw materials and international shipping. The currency of the country is the Lire. Naturally, the cost of living anywhere in the world depends on that person's lifestyle, the type of food, clothing, location and area of ​​residence, and so on. But the average monthly cost of living in the country is about anything between $ 4.9 to $ 4.9 (roughly $ 1- $ 3) a month. Tuition at public universities in Turkey is free. The cost of studying at private universities in Turkey is also about 1.5-1.3 lire per year and the cost of studying in semi-private universities is about 1.5-1.6 lire per year. The cost of education depends on the type of degree, degree and type of university. In general, living conditions in Turkey are more similar to Iran than to European countries.</p>

